<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Identity</strong> standardizes <strong>acquiring and managing a user's credentials behind
    one swappable provider</strong>. The browser's <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Credential_Management_API"><code>navigator.credentials</code></a>
    dispatcher is the normalized contract; passkey/WebAuthn, FedCM, digital-credential, and password are
    <em>families</em> resolved by a single <strong>credential provider</strong>. Swap a ceremony engine
    (SimpleWebAuthn, Hanko, a FedCM IdP) and the requesting surface is untouched.
  </p>
  <p>
    The provider is never baked into the surface — it is resolved through the injector chain: a native-first
    default ships (a <code>navigator.credentials</code> passthrough), the project selects or overrides it,
    and custom providers plug in. <strong>The provider contract is the only lock</strong>. Identity is the
    twin of <a href="/projects/webguards/">Web Guards</a>: it reuses Guard's <em>async,
    server-authoritative, revocable</em> contract verbatim — the browser only <em>gathers</em> a credential;
    the server <em>verifies</em> it. Identity <em>produces</em> the auth-state predicate that Guard's
    access-gate <em>consumes</em>.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #4f46e5; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #4338ca; font-size: 1rem;">The problem it solves</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      "Sign in with a passkey", "Sign in with Google", "Sign in with a saved password" look like three
      different integrations, each with its own SDK and ceremony. They are the same machine:
      <strong>a credential request, dispatched by family, resolved by a provider, verified on the
      server</strong>. Today every app re-wires WebAuthn, FedCM, and password autofill by hand and couples
      the ceremony library into the UI. Web Identity extracts the one reusable seam so a family is a
      <em>declared request dimension</em> and the engine behind it is swappable.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

