<section id="protocol-credential-management" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="how-it-works">Credential Management Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    A requesting surface never bundles a ceremony. It declares the <strong>families</strong> it accepts and
    the <strong>member</strong> it wants (request / enrollment / session-mediation), resolves the
    application's <strong>credential provider</strong> through the injector chain, and asks it. Dispatch is
    <strong>2-D</strong> — the protocol's dispatcher fans the request by <em>family</em> (which providers
    are registered for the requested <code>credentials:[…]</code>) <em>and</em> by <em>member</em> (which
    of those families support enrollment vs request vs sign-out).
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
// The seam — the ONLY lock. A credential provider answers a request for one family + member.
type CredentialFamily = 'passkey' | 'federated' | 'digital' | 'password';
type CredentialMember = 'credential-request' | 'credential-enrollment' | 'session-mediation';

interface CustomCredentialProvider {
  // Which families this provider serves, and which members each family supports
  // (e.g. FedCM/digital are request-only; passkey/password also enroll).
  readonly families: CredentialFamily[];
  supports(family: CredentialFamily, member: CredentialMember): boolean;

  // Async by default: acquiring a credential crosses a trust boundary (RP/IdP round-trip).
  // member 'credential-request'    -> navigator.credentials.get()
  // member 'credential-enrollment' -> navigator.credentials.create() / store()
  // member 'session-mediation'     -> navigator.credentials.preventSilentAccess()
  acquire(request: CredentialRequest): Promise<CredentialResult>;

  // Revocable: a session can be invalidated. Optional signal to re-mediate.
  subscribe?(onInvalidate: () => void): Cleanup;
}

interface CredentialRequest {
  member: CredentialMember;
  // The requesting surface lists the families it will accept; the dispatcher fans to their providers.
  credentials: CredentialFamily[];
  mediation?: 'silent' | 'optional' | 'conditional' | 'required';   // native enum, from the #482 intent
}

// 1. The application registers ONE provider per family (native-first default; project overrides it).
customCredentials.define('passkey', new SimpleWebAuthnProvider(rp));
injector Application {
  provide { credentials: 'passkey' } to '@web-identity';   // every descendant resolves this provider
}

// 2. A surface delegates — it owns only its affordance, never the ceremony.
const provider = InjectorRoot.getProviderOf(el, 'customCredentials');
const result = await provider.acquire({ member: 'credential-request', credentials: ['passkey', 'password'] });
if (result.ok) identity.signIn(result.descriptor);   // feeds the auth-state predicate Guard consumes
  {% endhighlight %}
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: 1rem;">
    <li><strong>One contract:</strong> <code>CustomCredentialProvider</code> — <code>acquire(request): Promise&lt;CredentialResult&gt;</code> — is satisfied by the native passthrough and every plugged ceremony engine alike.</li>
    <li><strong>One registry:</strong> <code>CustomCredentialRegistry</code> (<code>window.customCredentials</code>) holds the named providers per family; the project selects/overrides via the injector chain (defaults live in the platform config a project extends, shipped as flavors — the tool itself carries no default).</li>
    <li><strong>Native-first default:</strong> the default provider is a <code>navigator.credentials</code> passthrough (most-available); a <strong>mock in-memory conformance provider</strong> ships in the protocol's first slice so every downstream surface is demoable without a relying-party server.</li>
    <li><strong>Families are a request dimension, not three standards:</strong> a surface lists <code>credentials:[passkey|federated|digital|password]</code>; the dispatcher resolves each to its registered provider. Swapping one family out leaves the others untouched — the interop story.</li>
  </ul>

  <h4 id="member-dispatch" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">The lifecycle is an open member set, not a flat surface</h4>
  <p style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <code>CredentialsContainer</code> is <code>get</code>/<code>create</code>/<code>store</code>/<code>preventSilentAccess</code>,
    but family support is <strong>asymmetric</strong>: <code>get</code> is universal, <code>create</code>/<code>store</code>
    are passkey + password only, and <code>preventSilentAccess</code> is an origin-global sign-out. A flat
    single contract would force get-only families (FedCM, digital) to stub enrollment — the exact problem
    Guard's member structure solves. So the lifecycle is modelled as <strong>members</strong>, each declaring
    its supporting families:
  </p>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong><code>credential-request</code></strong> — <code>get()</code>, all families. The headline member.</li>
    <li><strong><code>credential-enrollment</code></strong> — <code>create()</code> / <code>store()</code>, passkey + password only. You cannot demo a passkey sign-in without first enrolling one — so enrollment is a sibling member, not out of scope.</li>
    <li><strong><code>session-mediation</code></strong> — <code>preventSilentAccess()</code>, origin-global sign-out / silent-access suppression.</li>
  </ul>

  <h4 id="provider-trust-boundary" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">The credential provider is Guard's contract, not the positioning provider</h4>
  <p style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    Web Identity reuses the <em>pattern</em> of <a href="/projects/webpositioning/">Anchor Positioning</a>'s
    provider (a named registry + injector-resolved contract, native-first), but its <strong>shape is
    Guard's</strong>: a credential request crosses a <strong>trust boundary</strong>, so the contract is —
  </p>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong>Async</strong> — <code>acquire()</code> returns a <code>Promise</code>; acquisition requires an RP/IdP round-trip.</li>
    <li><strong>Server-authoritative</strong> — the back-end verifies the assertion/token; the front-end request only <em>gathers</em> the credential. The standard is not to be mistaken for authentication.</li>
    <li><strong>Revocable</strong> — a session can be invalidated after sign-in; the optional <code>subscribe()</code> signal lets a surface re-mediate, and <code>session-mediation</code> suppresses silent re-auth.</li>
  </ul>

  <h4 id="rulings" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Design rulings (<a href="/backlog/496-webidentity-build-design-credential-acquisition-protocol-co/">#496</a>)</h4>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong>One <code>CustomCredentialProvider</code> per family, registry-resolved</strong> (Fork 1-A) — not a monolithic family-branching provider and not per-family contracts. The mock conformance provider ships in the first slice.</li>
    <li><strong>Lifecycle as three open members</strong> (Fork 2-A) — request / enrollment / session-mediation, each declaring supporting families; not acquisition-only (too thin) and not a flat four-method surface (stubs get-only families).</li>
    <li><strong>Protocol renamed <code>credential-acquisition</code> &rarr; <code>credential-management</code></strong> — once the member set expanded past <code>get</code>, the protocol <em>is</em> the full Credential Management API surface; the native anchor is literally that API.</li>
    <li><strong>Configurator domain omitted</strong> (Fork 3-A) — technical defaults ride the provider registry + config-flavors; an identity Configurator domain is carved to plateau-app as non-blocking <a href="/backlog/499-identity-ceremony-configurator-domain-plateau-app-explore-on/">#499</a>, added only on real authoring need.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section id="composition" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="composition">Composition With Other Standards</h3>
  <p>
    Web Identity owns <em>acquiring and managing the credential</em>, not who-may-do-what, not the browser's
    capability permissions, and not the UX of the request surface — those compose with neighbours:
  </p>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong><a href="/intents/web-identity/">Web Identity intent</a> (#482)</strong> — the thin, UX-only seam (mediation hint, request surface, auth-state signal). It declares the <em>request</em>; this protocol resolves the provider and ceremony behind it.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/projects/webguards/">Web Guards</a></strong> — identity <em>produces</em> the auth-state predicate; Guard's access-gate (<a href="/backlog/178-access-control-authorization-gate/">#178</a>) and presence-gate (<a href="/backlog/272-guard-protocol-predicate-gated-transitions-and-presence-open/">#272</a>) <em>consume</em> it. Authentication vs authorization — distinct concerns on one seam each.</li>
    <li><strong>Browser Permissions (webpermissions)</strong> — the native Permissions API (camera, geolocation) is a device-capability axis, not app-level identity; do not conflate.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/intents/loader/">Loader</a> / <a href="/intents/feedback/">Feedback</a></strong> — a non-<code>silent</code> mediation in flight drives the Loader intent; an auth-state transition is announced through Feedback — composed via the #482 intent, not re-invented here.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section id="status" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
  <p>
    Web Identity is in <strong>concept</strong> phase. The Credential Management protocol's seam (request +
    family dimension + member set + provider) is specified here and ruled by
    <a href="/backlog/496-webidentity-build-design-credential-acquisition-protocol-co/">#496</a>; the thin
    UX intent shipped as <a href="/intents/web-identity/">#482</a>. The provider implementation, the mock
    conformance provider, and the three members are the first planned work
    (<a href="/backlog/483-webidentity-project-credential-acquisition-protocol-deferred/">#483</a>), on top
    of this contract.
  </p>
  <h4 style="margin-top: 1rem;">Open Questions</h4>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    <li>Does <code>CredentialRequest</code> carry the RP/IdP config inline, or resolve it lazily inside the provider per origin?</li>
    <li>How does a multi-family request whose providers disagree (one returns, one rejects) resolve — first-success, or an explicit family preference order?</li>
    <li>Whether <code>session-mediation</code>'s origin-global scope needs a per-surface override for embedded contexts (iframes / portals).</li>
  </ul>
</section>
